OK, I did a bit of digging and the problem appears to be in Outlook. I'll
spare you the rant about M$ products and instead suggest you change the
values of the Incoming and Outgoing (SMTP) server address to the IP instead
of the mailserver name:

64.207.129.57 (this is mail.gridserver.com), or
216.70.64.104 (this is mail.indigometrics.com)

I.e., the problem appears to be the wildcard mailserver name (*.
gridserver.com), which Outlook takes exception to. If it wasn't set to *.
gridserver.com before, you can try that also. More info and debugging
options here:

https://www.slipstick.com/outlook/security-warnings-in-outlook/

https://www.wincert.net/microsoft-windows/the-target-principal-name-is-inco=
